      "examples": [
        {
          "title": "Description List Patterns: Glossary, Metadata, and FAQ",
          "description": "Shows three real-world uses of dl in a single page: a CSS glossary with one term per definition, an article metadata block with multiple values per term, and an FAQ where each question is a dt and the answer is a dd.",
          "code_snippet": "<!DOCTYPE html>\n<html lang=\"en\">\n  <head>\n    <meta charset=\"UTF-8\" />\n    <meta name=\"viewport\" content=\"width=device-width, initial-scale=1.0\" />\n    <title>Description List Patterns</title>\n    <style>\n      body { font-family: sans-serif; padding: 2rem; max-width: 720px; margin: 0 auto; }\n      h2 { color: #1a1a2e; }\n\n      /* Pattern 1: two-column glossary layout */\n      .glossary { display: grid; grid-template-columns: max-content 1fr; gap: 0.5rem 2rem; }\n      .glossary dt { font-weight: 700; color: #0077cc; }\n      .glossary dd { margin: 0; }\n\n      /* Pattern 2: metadata block */\n      .meta { display: grid; grid-template-columns: 130px 1fr; gap: 0.3rem 1rem; font-size: 0.9rem; }\n      .meta dt { font-weight: 600; color: #555; }\n      .meta dd { margin: 0; }\n\n      /* Pattern 3: FAQ */\n      .faq dt { font-weight: 700; margin-top: 1rem; }\n      .faq dd { margin-left: 0; color: #444; line-height: 1.6; }\n    </style>\n  </head>\n  <body>\n\n    <!-- Pattern 1: Glossary — one dt, one dd per entry -->\n    <h2>CSS Glossary</h2>\n    <dl class=\"glossary\">\n      <dt>Cascade</dt>\n      <dd>The algorithm that determines which CSS rules apply when multiple rules target the same element.</dd>\n\n      <dt>Specificity</dt>\n      <dd>A weight assigned to a CSS selector that determines which rule wins when rules conflict.</dd>\n\n      <dt>Inheritance</dt>\n      <dd>The mechanism by which some CSS properties are passed from parent elements to their children.</dd>\n    </dl>\n\n    <!-- Pattern 2: Article metadata — one dt, multiple dd values -->\n    <h2>Article Metadata</h2>\n    <dl class=\"meta\">\n      <dt>Author</dt>\n      <dd>Sarah Chen</dd>\n\n      <dt>Published</dt>\n      <dd>15 January 2024</dd>\n\n      <!-- One term with two values: dt shares multiple dd siblings -->\n      <dt>Tags</dt>\n      <dd>CSS</dd>\n      <dd>Web Standards</dd>\n      <dd>Frontend</dd>\n    </dl>\n\n    <!-- Pattern 3: FAQ — question as dt, answer as dd -->\n    <h2>FAQ</h2>\n    <dl class=\"faq\">\n      <dt>What browsers support CSS nesting?</dt>\n      <dd>All major browsers including Chrome 112+, Firefox 117+, and Safari 17+ support CSS nesting natively.</dd>\n\n      <dt>Do I need a preprocessor for CSS variables?</dt>\n      <dd>No. CSS custom properties are a native browser feature and require no build step or preprocessor.</dd>\n    </dl>\n\n  </body>\n</html>",
          "output": "The page shows three sections. The glossary renders as a two-column grid with blue bold terms on the left and definitions on the right. The metadata block shows label-value pairs where the Tags entry lists three values stacked under one label. The FAQ shows bold questions followed by paragraph-style answers. Screen readers traverse each dt and dd in sequence, associating each term with its description.",
          "images": null,
