      "slug": "nested-list-structures",
      "title": "Nested List Structures",
      "description": "Nested lists place a ul or ol inside an li to represent hierarchical content at multiple levels.",
      "content": [
        {
          "type": "paragraph",
          "text": [
            {
              "value": "A nested list is created by placing a "
            },
            {
              "value": "<ul>",
              "bold": true,
              "highlight": true,
              "link": "https://developer.mozilla.org/en-US/docs/Web/HTML/Element/ul"
            },
            {
              "value": " or "
            },
            {
              "value": "<ol>",
              "bold": true,
              "highlight": true,
              "link": "https://developer.mozilla.org/en-US/docs/Web/HTML/Element/ol"
            },
            {
              "value": " element "
            },
            {
              "value": "inside an",
              "bold": true
            },
            {
              "value": " "
            },
            {
              "value": "<li>",
              "bold": true,
              "highlight": true,
              "link": "https://developer.mozilla.org/en-US/docs/Web/HTML/Element/li"
            },
            {
              "value": " element of a parent list. The nested list must always be a child of an "
            },
            {
              "value": "<li>",
              "bold": true,
              "highlight": true
            },
            {
              "value": ", never a direct child of the parent "
            },
            {
              "value": "<ul>",
              "bold": true,
              "highlight": true
            },
            {
              "value": " or "
            },
            {
              "value": "<ol>",
              "bold": true,
              "highlight": true
            },
            {
              "value": ". Browsers apply progressively different default bullet styles at each level: filled circle at level one, open circle at level two, and filled square at level three. Screen readers announce the depth of each nested list, so users always know their position in the hierarchy. Lists can be mixed: an "
            },
            {
              "value": "<ol>",
              "bold": true,
              "highlight": true,
              "link": "https://developer.mozilla.org/en-US/docs/Web/HTML/Element/ol"
            },
            {
              "value": " can nest inside a "
            },
            {
              "value": "<ul>",
              "bold": true,
              "highlight": true
            },
            {
              "value": " and vice versa when the content warrants it."
            }
          ]
        },
        {
          "type": "callout",
          "variant": "warning",
          "title": "Never place a list directly inside another list",
          "text": "Placing a ul or ol as a direct child of another ul or ol without wrapping it in an li is invalid HTML. Browsers silently correct it, but the item count reported to screen readers becomes wrong and the nesting depth is lost."
        }
      ],
      "examples": [
        {
          "title": "Multi-level Navigation Menu and Document Outline",
          "description": "Shows two common nested list patterns: a three-level site navigation menu using nested ul elements, and a document outline mixing ol and ul to represent chapters with unordered sub-points.",
          "code_snippet": "<!DOCTYPE html>\n<html lang=\"en\">\n  <head>\n    <meta charset=\"UTF-8\" />\n    <meta name=\"viewport\" content=\"width=device-width, initial-scale=1.0\" />\n    <title>Nested List Examples</title>\n    <style>\n      body { font-family: sans-serif; padding: 2rem; max-width: 700px; }\n      h2 { color: #1a1a2e; }\n\n      /* Navigation menu styles */\n      nav ul { list-style: none; padding: 0; margin: 0; }\n      nav > ul > li { margin-bottom: 0.25rem; }\n      nav a { text-decoration: none; color: #0077cc; display: block; padding: 0.3rem 0; }\n      nav a:hover { color: #005fa3; }\n      /* Indent nested levels visually */\n      nav ul ul { padding-left: 1.25rem; border-left: 2px solid #e0e0e0; margin-top: 0.25rem; }\n    </style>\n  </head>\n  <body>\n\n    <!-- Pattern 1: Nested ul for site navigation -->\n    <h2>Site Navigation</h2>\n    <nav aria-label=\"Site map\">\n      <ul role=\"list\">\n        <li><a href=\"/\">Home</a></li>\n        <li>\n          <a href=\"/docs\">Documentation</a>\n          <!-- Nested ul MUST be inside the li, not after it -->\n          <ul role=\"list\">\n            <li><a href=\"/docs/start\">Getting Started</a></li>\n            <li>\n              <a href=\"/docs/api\">API Reference</a>\n              <!-- Third level nesting -->\n              <ul role=\"list\">\n                <li><a href=\"/docs/api/auth\">Authentication</a></li>\n                <li><a href=\"/docs/api/users\">Users</a></li>\n              </ul>\n            </li>\n            <li><a href=\"/docs/examples\">Examples</a></li>\n          </ul>\n        </li>\n        <li><a href=\"/blog\">Blog</a></li>\n        <li><a href=\"/contact\">Contact</a></li>\n      </ul>\n    </nav>\n\n    <!-- Pattern 2: Mixed ol/ul for a document outline -->\n    <h2>Course Outline</h2>\n    <!-- ol for chapters: order is meaningful -->\n    <ol>\n      <li>\n        Introduction to HTML\n        <!-- ul for topics inside the chapter: order is not critical -->\n        <ul>\n          <li>History and evolution</li>\n          <li>Document structure basics</li>\n          <li>Setting up a development environment</li>\n        </ul>\n      </li>\n      <li>\n        Semantic Elements\n        <ul>\n          <li>Sectioning elements</li>\n          <li>Text-level semantics</li>\n          <li>Embedded content</li>\n        </ul>\n      </li>\n      <li>\n        Forms and Validation\n        <ul>\n          <li>Input types and attributes</li>\n          <li>Constraint validation API</li>\n        </ul>\n      </li>\n    </ol>\n\n  </body>\n</html>",
          "output": "The navigation section shows a vertically stacked link list. 'Documentation' expands visually to show three indented child links, with 'API Reference' further indented to reveal two more links, all separated by a thin left border. The course outline shows three numbered chapters, each with a bulleted sub-list of topics. Screen readers announce each nested list as a new list with its own item count and nesting level.",
          "images": null,
          "video_url": null
        }
      ],
      "image_banner_url": null,
      "images": null,
      "video_url": null,
      "when_to_use": [],
      "when_to_avoid": [],
      "what_it_solves": [],
      "conceptual_understanding": [
        {
          "text": [
            {
              "value": "A nested list is like a folder structure on a computer: the top-level "
            },
            {
              "value": "<ul>",
              "bold": true,
              "highlight": true,
              "link": "https://developer.mozilla.org/en-US/docs/Web/HTML/Element/ul"
            },
            {
              "value": " is the root drive, each "
            },
            {
              "value": "<li>",
              "bold": true,
              "highlight": true,
              "link": "https://developer.mozilla.org/en-US/docs/Web/HTML/Element/li"
            },
            {
              "value": " is a folder, and the nested "
            },
            {
              "value": "<ul>",
              "bold": true,
              "highlight": true
            },
            {
              "value": " inside it is a subfolder. Assistive technologies read the depth the same way a file manager reads the folder level, always telling you where you are in the hierarchy."
            }
          ],
          "type": "paragraph"
        },
        {
          "text": [
            {
              "value": "Mixing "
            },
            {
              "value": "<ol>",
              "bold": true,
              "highlight": true,
              "link": "https://developer.mozilla.org/en-US/docs/Web/HTML/Element/ol"
            },
            {
              "value": " and "
            },
            {
              "value": "<ul>",
              "bold": true,
              "highlight": true,
              "link": "https://developer.mozilla.org/en-US/docs/Web/HTML/Element/ul"
            },
            {
              "value": " in nested lists is like a book's table of contents: chapters are numbered ("
            },
            {
              "value": "<ol>",
              "bold": true,
              "highlight": true
            },
            {
              "value": ") because their order defines the narrative arc, but the topics within each chapter are bulleted ("
            },
            {
              "value": "<ul>",
              "bold": true,
              "highlight": true
            },
            {
              "value": ") because they can be covered in any order without breaking the chapter's meaning."
            }
          ],
          "type": "paragraph"
        }
      ],
      "common_mistakes": [],
      "bonus_tips": [
        {
          "text": [
            {
              "value": "When using "
            },
            {
              "value": "list-style: none",
              "bold": true,
              "highlight": true,
              "link": "https://developer.mozilla.org/en-US/docs/Web/CSS/list-style"
            },
            {
              "value": " on a nested navigation "
            },
            {
              "value": "<ul>",
              "bold": true,
              "highlight": true,
              "link": "https://developer.mozilla.org/en-US/docs/Web/HTML/Element/ul"
            },
            {
              "value": " in Safari, add "
            },
            {
              "value": "role=\"list\"",
              "bold": true,
              "highlight": true,
              "link": "https://developer.mozilla.org/en-US/docs/Web/Accessibility/ARIA/Roles/list_role"
            },
            {
              "value": " to every "
            },
            {
              "value": "<ul>",
              "bold": true,
              "highlight": true
            },
            {
              "value": " at every nesting level, not just the outermost one. Safari strips the list role from all levels independently when the style is applied."
            }
          ],
          "type": "paragraph"
        }
      ],
